[4] Argentina (Choco)
Date: Tue 24 Mar 2009
Source: Diario Los Andes [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.losandes.com.ar/notas/2009/3/24/un-414980.asp>


Chaco's government confirmed that there were 784 confirmed cases of
dengue in the province, while neighbors and the municipal authorities
of Charat called for aerial spraying in the area, after expired
insecticides had been used. The number of cases was confirmed by the
Minister of Health of the province, Sandra Mendoza. "On 14 Jan
[2009], a health alert was declared, and starting on that date, a
continuing intensified campaign is monitoring indices of [_Aedes
aegypti_ vector mosquito] infestation in different locations in the
interior province," said the official, who also said that there are
34 cities affected by the disease.

Mendoza said that dengue in Chaco "is not an epidemic, but an
outbreak, which is controlled because work started on prevention
before suspected [dengue] cases appeared." [But] The mayor of the city
said: "This outbreak has already become an epidemic, with more than
6000 suspected dengue cases in just Charat,
that began more than 45 days ago."

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT <promed@promedmail.org>

[In the 28 Mar 2009 edition of Univision (in Spanish)
<http://www.univision.com/contentroot/wirefeeds/salud/7916450.html>,
the Minister of Health on Thursday (26 Mar 2009) confirmed the
existence of a dengue outbreak in the northern part of the country,
indicating that there are 2200 confirmed cases of dengue in the
country, of which 1200 are in the province of Chaco, about 1000 km
north of Buenos Aires. However, the mayor of the town of Chaco
Charat, Miguel Weaver, told the newspaper Clarin that the number of
dengue patients in the province totaled 6000.

The 24 Mar 2009 edition of El Diario Argentino.com (in Spanish)
<http://www.eldiarioargentino.com/salud-nota.php?idx=5974>
said that Hugo Fernandez, director of Disease Prevention in the Health
Ministry, recognized the existence of more than 980 cases in Chaco and
felt that this is an "outbreak." The official also noted that the peak
intensity of the disease occurs in Argentina in April. However, the
mayor of Charat, Miguel Weaver, argued that, in this population of
western Chaco, "there are about 100 patients per day or more," in a
conversation with this agency. He added, "This is not 5, 10 or 20
cases; this is an epidemic."

This raises the question as to when an "outbreak" becomes an
"epidemic." In any event, in this part of Chaco, the number of cases
appears to be increasing, even if the above figures are conflicting,
and one hopes that provincial and national health agencies are
successful in bringing down the numbers of new cases and providing
timely and effective treatment of cases to avoid fatalities.

A map of Argentina showing the provinces mentioned can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/argentina_pol_1996.pdf>.
A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Argentina can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/promed/en?v=-35.4,-64.2,5>.
- Mod.TY]

