[7] Indonesia (West Java)
Date: Mon 23 Mar 2009
Source: The Jakarta Post [edited]
<http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2009/03/23/47-die-dengue-fever-west-java.html>


The West Java administration has declared all its municipalities and
regencies under threat from dengue fever, after local authorities
recorded more than 6000 cases of the disease, 47 of them fatal, as of
March this year [2009].

Wahyu Saputra, head of the provincial health agency's disease control
section, told The Jakarta Post on Friday [20 Mar 2009] that of the
affected areas, Depok had recorded the most cases (637), followed by
Sumedang, Garut, Subang and Purwakarta districts with more than 300
infections each.

But he added the figures were slightly down from those in the same
period last year [2008], when more than 6800 cases were recorded, 65
of them fatal.

"To prevent the figures from rising, we are focusing on campaigning
for a healthy environment. We're also providing information on
symptoms of the mosquito-borne disease to prevent more fatalities,"
Wahyu said.

--
